They lost in the final seconds, and showed up completely flat in Arrowhead. Despite racking up 417 yards against New Orleans, the 49ers mustered just a field goal until garbage time. They had only 4 first downs in the first half to Kansas City's 13. They converted just 4-of-17 third downs, and allowed the Chiefs to accumulate 5 sacks.    I don't want to take anything away from the Chiefs though. They were very impressive defensively, holding Frank Gore to just 43 yards on 15 carries. Alex Smith (23-of-42, 232 yards, 1 TD, 1 INT) had absolutely no time to throw. Tamba Hali sacked Smith on 3 occasions.    Matt Cassel also played well for the first time all year. He went 16-of-27 for 250 yards, 3 touchdowns and an interception. Cassel's first score was all Dexter McCluster, who led the team with 69 receiving yards off 3 catches. Cassel's second touchdown was a flea flicker out of the Wildcat to Dwayne Bowe (2 catches, 61 yards). The third was a great throw to Tony Moeaki (4-44), who made an outstanding 1.handed grab.    Jamaal Charles once again had fewer carries than Thomas Jones. Despite this, Charles had more rushing yards - which shouldn't surprise anyone except for Todd Haley. Charles turned 12 rushes into 97 yards, while Jones had 19 attempts go for 95 yards and a score. Charles also had 3 catches for 57 receiving yards.    As for San Francisco, Gore was able to save his fantasy day with 9 catches for 102 receiving yards. He was the only 49er to have more than 3 catches, including Michael Crabtree (3-37) and Vernon Davis (3-22).

Tony Romo was the third quarterback in 3 weeks to torch Houston's secondary. He didn't get to 400 yards like Peyton Manning and Donovan McNabb, but that's because Dallas led throughout. Romo finished 23-of-30 for 284 yards and 2 touchdowns.    Both of Romo's scores sadly went to the useless Roy Williams, who actually put forth some effort today. Williams caught 5 balls for 117 yards.    Jason Witten had 7 grabs for 56 yards. Miles Austin-Jones didn't do much (2-20), while Dez Bryant (4-50) nearly came up with 2 touchdowns of his own. Bryant caught a pass in the end zone, but was pushed out of bounds in mid-air by the defender, which ruled the play incomplete. Bryant later had a long run for a touchdown, but that was wiped out by a penalty.    Tom Jackson won't have an aneurysm this week because the Cowboys actually ran the ball for a change. Dallas gave 26 carries to Marion Barber, Felix Jones and Tashard Choice, most of which went to the former (17 rushes, 55 yards, TD). Felix Jones had 7 attempts for 43 yards.    Matt Schaub struggled, though that's understandable because he didn't have his left tackle against Dallas' superb defense. Schaub went 23-of-32 for 241 yards, 1 touchdown and 2 interceptions. DeMarcus Ware fully took advantage of the hole on Schaub's blind side, as he racked up 3 sacks.    Andre Johnson led Houston's receivers with 4 catches for 64 yards despite not being 100 percent. Johnson left the game briefly after re-injuring his ankle.    Arian Foster was the 1 bright spot for the Texans' offense; he had 106 yards on 17 carries, along with 4 catches for 20 receiving yards.

games.comments: When the schedule came out, the Falcons circled this game. They lost 2 close contests to the Saints last year, so they saw this NFC South clash as a measuring stick to see how good they are. I imagine that everyone in Atlanta is pleased with the result.    If you're a fan of old-school, pound-the-rock football, you loved what the Falcons did in New Orleans. Atlanta ran the ball 44 times, which allowed them to win the time-of-possession battle by about 18-and-a-half minutes. On 1 impressive possession, the Falcons held the ball for almost 12 minutes. They converted back-to-back 4.h downs on the drive and eventually scored a touchdown. Mike Smith deserves a ton of credit for eschewing a field goal attempt on those 2 occasions. Michael Turner had 30 of Atlanta's 44 carries, and turned those attempts into 114 yards and a touchdown. Jason Snelling had 62 yards on 14 rushes.    Matt Ryan had an excellent game, going 19-of-30 for 228 yards and 2 scores. He also scrambled 6 times for 26 rushing yards. Ryan's scores went to Tony Gonzalez and Roddy White (5 catches, 69 yards). Gonzalez silenced all critics (including myself) who speculated that he might be done after 2 poor games. Gonzalez hauled in 8 balls for 110 yards.    Drew Brees went 30-of-38 for 365 yards, 3 touchdowns and 2 picks. He did well enough to set the Saints up with a game-winning field goal in overtime, but Garrett Hartley uncharacteristically blew a chip-shot 29-yarder in overtime. Sean Payton actually mentioned Hartley's missed kick in the post-game press conference as a reason for why his team lost. Perhaps Payton forgot the instance where he foolishly gave scrub running back Chris Ivory a 4.h-down carry instead of Pierre Thomas (9 carries, 30 yards; 6 catches, 61 rec. yards). Ivory coughed up the football.    People who watched this game witnessed the rebirth of Lance Moore. As in 2008 when Reggie Bush got hurt, Moore became a huge part of the offense, catching 6 balls for 149 yards and 2 touchdowns.    While Marques Colston did nothing (4-25), Jeremy Shockey notched 8 receptions for 78 yards and a score.

Would they give a spirited performance like the Bengals last year (Chris Henry), or understandably be completely flat like Redskins in 2007 (Sean Taylor)? Well, despite the 2.touchdown loss, Denver was very solid. But in addition to being overmatched against an elite Colts team, the Broncos had way too many failed trips in the red zone. Laurence Maroney couldn't get into the end zone on 4th-and-goal in the second quarter. At the end of the game, Denver gave the ball up on downs on back-to-back possessions inside the Indianapolis 20.    Kyle Orton went 37-of-57 for 476 yards, 1 touchdown and an interception. His score was a beautiful 48-yard bomb to Brandon Lloyd. Lloyd put on a monstrous performance, catching 6 balls for 169 yards and that score. Jabar Gaffney also posted big numbers (12 catches, 140 yards) despite the presence of Demaryius Thomas. Thomas had 2 grabs for 43 yards, and almost pulled in a touchdown. However, Thomas suffered a hand injury at the end of the game.    With Knowshon Moreno out, Laurence Maroney got the start. It wasn't pretty. Instead, Austin Collie (12-171, 2 TDs) dominated. As for Manning's other targets, Dallas Clark had 5 grabs for 44 yards. Rookie Blair White stepped in for an injured Pierre Garcon, and recorded 3 catches for 27 yards and a score.    Like the Broncos, the Colts struggled to run the ball. Joseph Addai mustered just 29 yards on 13 attempts. Donald Brown didn't get many touches until late in the game when the Colts had a 14-point lead.
